    <stitle>INTERNATIONAL RIDE OPTIMIZED SUSPENSION (IROS) - AIR LINES</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
        <title>AIR LINES</title>
        <para>Air is supplied to the air springs (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0301312">Figure 12, Item 10</hotlnk>) from the air system. There are two delivery ports in
            the height control valve supplying air to the right and left air springs.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0301312" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg03/g0301312.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                     scalefitheight="312px"/>
            <caption>Figure 12. Air Spring Hosing and Valves</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. CURB SIDE AIR SPRING SUPPLY LINE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. CHASSIS CROSSMEMBER</callout1>
                <callout1>3. STREET SIDE AIR SPRING SUPPLY LINE</callout1>
                <callout1>4. STREET SIDE FRAME RAIL SECTION</callout1>
                <callout1>5. AIR SPRING UPPER MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                <callout1>6. STREET SIDE AIR SPRING</callout1>
                <callout1>7. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                <callout1>8. LOWER AIR VALVE BRACKET</callout1>
                <callout1>9. HEIGHT CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                <callout1>10. MAIN AIR SUPPLY LINE FROM AIR TANK</callout1>
                <callout1>11. CURB SIDE AIR SPRING</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>Air lines between the air springs (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0301312">Figure 12, Items 1 and 3</hotlnk>) provide air flow transfer across the axle to
            maintain constant frame rail height and equal distribution at the axle ends.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
